content: Hello friends, lets begin the lesson!
I hope you all saw the announcements, so you didnt have to come here too early.
Next week the lesson will be in normal time.
Today we will discuss about i11 opening variant.
This 5th move is something that keeps catching my eyes in past months.
What is your impression about this 6th move?
black can make mistake easier in this variant
No much feeling coz I seldom play it
i like this type of move
I meant, that this can be good for white
it gives to much space to black on downside

I find some words from old theory lessons:"the white can be active for some time, but finally when white activity is over, black will be powerful.", but seems maybe white can be better than those words
i must be good for black
maybe it is a good point for white
Indeed, we often change our evaluations in times.
The best example is the d11 opening,
which has changed in the range of nearly white win to nearly black win
about i11 variant, with this 6th move,
it has not changed much though.
but indeed, black will eventually get the control.
But it is a matter of skill and techniques,
and turn it into the success.
The practical games at ORC game server have shown,
that many people are confused about black plans,
and so they fail to make a serious attack.
where to strongest players of the city, Kareev and Skuridin met.
we saw his game quite recently.
but Skuridin may be unfamiliar to many of you.
I first met and played with Skuridin in 1989 in the same city
Indeed, for those who know more about WC,
I played with Skuridin a lot at Gambler last year
Skuridin was the referee of the AT of WC
I have gotten two losses from him in the past.
One was the i12 opening gamble,
where I did not find black win,
how many games did you play
I forgot how many times we have met finally.
Kareev and Skuridin were about evenly strong opponents in 1999.
so RT is absolutely better than him:)
Today, perhaps Kareev is a bit better.
Skuridin is a famous fan of this variant.
Everybody knows it is one of his favorites.
He has used this white tactics against many players,
and for my surprise, he is still quite successful.
Nearly all games of this variant go through same 11 moves.
Now, I have seen many 13th moves.
If you were black, where would you play the next move?
Japanese theory recommends g11 for over 25 years.
And when the renju spred to Europe,
most European players adopted this theory without questions.
Therefore people repeatedly played this move, without questioning other possibilities.
Yes, adopting without anlyse not good, but timespreading :)
White can be more gambling, by playing 14-k9,
but eventually black is quite comfortable
anyway, those who feel interested, may study this variant more deeply by themselves.
if white can defend, it is pretty good then,
but it seems the upper left corner is quite scary
the Nizhny Novgorod players announced black sure win here.
Then Ants Soosyrv replied to them,
And there has not been any further comments by NN players,
however, they seem to have started to use this white tactics more frequently after that.
There are two interesting issues here.
and preparing ground for round development,
But k10 is completely different style.
Have you seen this move before?
This was the move the NN players claimed to be sure win over 10 years ago.
Truth or not, hard to say. According to Ants, it is not a win. And the fact that they peacefully use it even today also shows there should not be too big risks involved.
11 years ago, Nizhny Novgorod was called by another name - Gorky.
it is the place where the two rives - Volga and Oka - meet.
This 16 seems to be the only defending move.
And it was also played by SKuridin in all his games.
Before we go on, and see further, let us take a moment and check some 'not-so-good' 16th moves.
RT, maybe you can place the article about renju history in Library?
Is here anyone, who would like to challenge this, and try black moves, if yes, say ME.
Liu, there are much better history writers than me.
I would be happy if they write more for us.
so, who will be black? say me.

scm2000, luwenzhe, Red_Zombie, SamSite, mikn1, HEX77, slamduk, alcore, strul, mayhem, yyfcsd, mcmanus, Aurora, span, LiuJianping, callings, Silver, Xespok, shuwang, weigui, Andry, dhalsim, casar, hunyi, NANYIN, liuwenming, Before, virag, sunrain, concord2497, H8, ouyang, bm, Jay, Intotherenju, sosei, fallnavy, coco_yuang, FIFAWORLDCUP, pantrike.
do you want to change or withdraw?
dont worry, its just a training
even if you are not sure, you can still try
it is the best way to learn.
/agrees with RT on saturday you will be very active
transform to different order of moves I think
do you want to change anything?
its a good feeling to win over RT
come on let tell RT how strong we are
maybe black should use more hidden possibilities,
black get more power in the under side
39 showed that black can even attack there
I was going to talk about 17-e8
and I am so happy that Samsite said "me" just before it
For white it is hard to make a good decision for next move.
Black takes a good control over lower side.
That is why the 16th move to L11 is not good.
This series of moves is a common struggle in such patterns.
but in this case, there is a problematic g11 stone,
so it becomes possible to block from the outside,
I am sure, Skuridin expected that,
let us all be one big and active team
j10 and j13 both seem reasonable.
j13 is better for upper defense,
if there are two defense moves,
then white should choose the one that its most beneficial for self in future.
maybe the stone at j10 looks too passive and inside
but if we assume that upper side is a "dead area" for both anyway,
then we think, how the materials of upper fight influence the left and right wings, which are currently quite empty and free.
and maybe the stone 20 can be more helpful there,
blocking against 10th horizontal line on the right side,
so, in my opinion, this ugly inside 20 is better this time,
I can't see reason to block it on the upper side
the upper side is dead anyway
but it is not enough for us, to make the decision.
namely, we must think of outcome,
no matter of how we block,
black can use the other end, to develop towards lower side.
and we need to evaluate the impact of that development for both cases.
even if we block at h10,
maybe the L14 will create enough support for attacks like m10,
so finally black will come out with bigger forces than we expected.
so, remember, we need to compare not only the are alone, (dead or not), but the usefulness of the black material, in developing towards new areas.
In this case, I would say,
it is not very easy to evaluate.
that is why your answers were quite 50-50
In my opnion it seems easier for black to develop after down stop
at least the important thing is that you understand why you decide for one or another move,
strul, here black has good development towards left
yes i know but seems harder in my eyes
so, we have to evaluate the outcomes of both areas
and make final decision according to that.
the fact alone that the upper area is dead is not always sufficient reason
yet, Kareev keeps attacking here on right,
It would be logical that he switches the sides now.
Perhaps he just uses some filling technique,
sometimes the filling is effective indeed.
The right win is very solid now,
and its time to move to left.
Did black need to use the four?
ok you all know the basic principle, we compare two outcomes
i think G9 is improtant point for black
if the second variant is better for black
then black didnt need to play the four
i would spend lots of time myself here,
to decide over the usage of black four to g9
yes, black is definitely looking good here.
lets see the variant of using the four
doesn't look so good to me
so, the best way is to evaluate the outcomes
and since we realized that white was not going to play to g9 anyway,
so there was no hurry to play black four there.
this is how we need to think about every four in renju game.
by the 37th move black is dying.
Having lost every chance to attack,
maybe white can make some changes,
but currently, all is going by white's happy tactics.
This is what happens to black in such variant,
if they attack without clear concept.
the active style ends up with poor result.
If 15-k10 is not sure win then it is a bad move,
but it takes very hard thinking
and this game shows how it usually ends in such case.
Let us see the possible outcome.
This game was a result of good tactics.
Opponent who was not prepared there,
That should make you all very careful,
else you might face the same destiny.
Maybe tomorrow, someone plays this against you in ORC game center,
and you will have a headache.
So, I hope you can all study it a bit, and make your own plans,
so you cannot be surprised by evil opponents. :)
This is the end of lesson, thank you all for coming. We see next week!
